      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0648P0-05477'>
        <a name='S5LV0648P0_20030604_GCR_61'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-jeff-rooker' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0648P0_20030604_GCR_61' title='Link to this speech by Mr Jeff Rooker' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-jeff-rooker" title="Mr Jeff Rooker">Lord Rooker</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I cannot answer the detail of that question but the resources of a particular authority will not be altered by the measure that we are discussing. Wherever the receipts come from and whatever the pooling arrangements may be, the resources of a particular authority will not be altered by the provision in subsection (5). It is purely an administrative measure. It is not even, as it were, central to policy. If it were not included, money would flow in two directions: money that the Government may pay to an authority and money that the Government expect to receive from an authority. It simply does not make sense for cheques to flow in two directions. As I say, the resources of a particular authority remain unaltered but the provision may result in someone saving the postage required in sending a cheque.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
