            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_241gc' title='Col. 241GC &mdash; HL Deb 04 June 2003 vol 648 c241GC' name='column_241gc' href='#column_241gc' rel='bookmark'>241GC</a>
            change our opinion, bearing in mind the report from the Audit Commission, which we cannot ignore. We do not want to use the power. We have included it in case authorities do not remedy the deficiencies set out in auditors' assessments, in which case action could be taken. We are working on the basis that the regulations would apply only to authorities that disregarded the advice of their chief financial officers.</p><p>
            That gives a long-stop measure to local government, not just the Audit Commission and the auditors. If the chief financial officer has told an authority that it is ready for serious trouble but it ignores the warning, action can be taken. I cannot conceive of a local council doing that. Just because we cannot conceive of it happening&#x2014;with reasonable professional people, as the noble Lord said&#x2014;does not mean that it will not happen. There have been financial difficulties with some authorities. I am not saying that the problems would be strictly analogous.</p><p>
            I do not wish to wind up the noble Lord, Lord Hanningfield, any further but I cannot accept that, when a little local problem arises, the authority should stop running the roads. Just because another difficulty has arisen, we should not knock out a service that people expect and that their council tax has paid for.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0648P0-05638'>
        <a name='S5LV0648P0_20030604_GCR_222'>  </a>
